Duff&#x27;s is not just about unrolling, it&#x27;s mostly a way to use the &#x27;case can be anywhere inside a switch statement&#x27;. It&#x27;s used a lot for other purpose, some of them very, very handy. The stackless coroutine trick is very useful for example (see <a href="http://www.chiark.greenend.org.uk/~sgtatham/coroutines.html" rel="nofollow">http://www.chiark.greenend.org.uk/~sgtatham/coroutines.html</a> )
On platforms with very little RAM (embedded) it&#x27;s fantastic to be able to &#x27;port&#x27; linear code that might have run in a thread, and convert it to a coroutine that is a lot easier to read and maintain than having to convert it all up to a &#x27;manual&#x27; state machine.<p>Note that with gcc, you can reach the same results by using the &#x27;indirect goto&#x27; that is both more powerful, and more dangerous!
  void * lab;
  lab = &my_label;
  goto *lab;
  my_label: ...
